WEBVTT

00:22.860 --> 00:27.740
XII. BRUTE NEIGHBOURS.

00:29.160 --> 00:33.860
Sometimes I had a companion in my fishing, who came through the village to my house

00:33.860 --> 00:39.460
from the other side of town, and the catching of the dinner was as much a social exercise

00:39.460 --> 00:48.840
as the eating of it—Hermit. I wonder what the world is doing now. I have not heard so

00:48.840 --> 00:54.820
much as a locust over the sweet fern these three hours. The pigeons are all asleep upon

00:54.820 --> 01:02.560
their roosts. No flutter from them. Was that a farmer's noon horn which sounded from beyond

01:02.560 --> 01:10.700
the woods just now? The hands are coming in to boiled salt beef and cider and Indian bread.

01:11.780 --> 01:22.380
Why will men worry themselves so? He that does not eat need not work. I wonder how much

01:22.380 --> 01:28.840
they have reaped. Who would live there where a body can never think for the barking of

01:28.840 --> 01:39.260
boasts? And, oh, the housekeeping! To keep bright the devil's doorknobs and scour his

01:39.260 --> 01:49.680
tubs this bright day, better not keep a house. Say, some hollow tree, and then for morning

01:49.680 --> 02:01.440
dinner parties. Only a woodpecker tapping. Oh, they swarm. The sun is too warm there.

02:01.580 --> 02:10.240
They are born too far into life for me. I have water from the spring and a loaf of brown

02:10.240 --> 02:18.980
bread on the shelf. Hark! I hear a rustling of the leaves. Is it some ill-fed village

02:18.980 --> 02:25.620
hound yielding to the instinct of the chase, or the lost pig which is said to be in these

02:25.620 --> 02:34.200
woods, whose tracks I saw after the rain? It comes on apace. My sumacs and sweetbriars

02:34.200 --> 02:35.100
tremble.

02:36.160 --> 02:42.340
Eh? Mr. Poet, is it you? How do you like the world today?

02:44.100 --> 02:53.480
Poet, see those clouds, how they hang. That's the greatest thing I have seen today. There's

02:53.480 --> 02:59.640
nothing like it in old paintings, nothing like it in foreign lands, unless when we were

02:59.640 --> 03:08.300
off the coast of Spain. That's a true Mediterranean sky. I thought as I have my living to get,

03:08.300 --> 03:14.360
and have not eaten today, that I might go a-fishing. That's the true industry for poets.

03:15.340 --> 03:20.640
It is the only trade I have learned. Come, let's along.

03:22.560 --> 03:31.180
Hermit, I cannot resist. My brown bread will soon be gone. I will go with you gladly soon.

03:31.900 --> 03:37.620
But I am just concluding a serious meditation. I think that I am near the end of it.

03:37.620 --> 03:43.940
Leave me alone, then, for a while. But that we may not be delayed, you shall be digging

03:43.940 --> 03:50.180
the bait, meanwhile. Angle-worms are rarely to be met with in these parts where the soil

03:50.180 --> 03:57.320
was never fattened with manure. The race is nearly extinct. The sport of digging the bait

03:57.320 --> 04:03.700
is nearly equal to that of catching the fish, when one's appetite is not too keen, and this

04:03.700 --> 04:10.320
you may have all to yourself today. I would advise you to set in the spade down yonder

04:10.320 --> 04:17.020
among the ground-nuts, where you see the John's-wort waving. I think that I may warrant you one

04:17.020 --> 04:23.080
worm to every three sods you turn up, if you look well in among the roots of the grass,

04:23.660 --> 04:30.620
as if you were weaving, or if you choose to go farther it will not be unwise. For I have

04:30.620 --> 04:35.800
found the increase of fair bait to be very nearly as the squares of the distances.

04:37.600 --> 04:48.100
Hermit alone. Let me see, where was I? Methinks I was nearly in this frame of mind. The world

04:48.100 --> 04:59.680
lay about at this angle. Shall I go to heaven, or a fishing? If I should soon bring this

04:59.940 --> 05:06.760
meditation to an end, would another so sweet occasion be likely to offer? I was as near

05:06.760 --> 05:15.600
being resolved into the essence of things as ever I was in my life. I fear my thoughts

05:15.600 --> 05:24.260
will not come back to me. If it would do any good I would whistle for them. When they make

05:24.260 --> 05:34.480
us an offer, is it wise to say we will think of it? My thoughts have left no track, and

05:34.480 --> 05:43.700
I cannot find the path again. What was it that I was thinking of? And was a very hazy

05:43.700 --> 05:54.640
day. I will just try these three sentences of confuzzi. They may fetch that state about

05:54.640 --> 06:04.860
again. I know not whether it was the dumps or a budding ecstasy. Mem, there never is

06:04.860 --> 06:16.060
but one opportunity of a kind. Poet. How now, Hermit? Is it too soon? I have got just thirteen

06:16.060 --> 06:21.500
whole ones, besides several which are imperfect or undersized, but they will do for the smaller

06:21.500 --> 06:34.840
fry. They do not cover up the hook so much. Those village worms are quite too large. A

06:34.840 --> 06:41.400
Well then, let's be off, shall we, to Concord? There's good sport there if the water be not

06:41.400 --> 06:52.280
too high. Why do precisely these objects which we behold make a world? Why has man just these

06:52.280 --> 06:58.360
species of animals for his neighbors as if nothing but a mouse could have filled this

06:58.960 --> 07:08.260
I suspect that Pilpe and company have put animals to their best use, for they are all

07:08.260 --> 07:17.160
beasts of burden, in a sense, made to carry some portion of our thoughts. The mice which

07:17.160 --> 07:21.780
haunted my house were not the common ones, which are said to have been introduced into

07:21.780 --> 07:29.340
the country, but a wild native kind not found in the village. I sent one to a distinguished

07:29.340 --> 07:36.700
naturalist and it interested him much. When I was building one of these had its nest underneath

07:36.700 --> 07:42.920
the house, and before I had laid the second floor and swept out the shavings would come

07:42.920 --> 07:48.740
out regularly at lunchtime and pick up the crumbs at my feet. It probably had never seen

07:48.740 --> 07:55.360
a man before, and it soon became quite familiar and would run over my shoes and up my clothes.

07:56.480 --> 08:02.280
It could readily ascend the sides of the room by short impulses like a squirrel, which it

08:02.280 --> 08:08.940
resembled in its motions. At length, as I leaned with my elbow on the bench one day,

08:09.580 --> 08:15.060
it ran up my clothes and along my sleeve and round and round the paper which held my dinner,

08:15.760 --> 08:22.520
while I kept the latter close and dodged and played at Bo Peep with it, and when at last

08:22.520 --> 08:28.980
I held still a piece of cheese between my thumb and finger, it came and nibbled it sitting

08:28.980 --> 08:39.180
in my hand, and afterward cleaned its face and paws like a fly and walked away. A Phoebe

08:39.560 --> 08:47.800
soon built in my shed, and a robin for protection in a pine which grew against the house. In

08:47.800 --> 08:56.460
June the partridge Tetrao Ombellus, which is so shy a bird, led her brood past my windows,

08:57.340 --> 09:02.420
from the woods in the rear to the front of my house, plucking and calling to them like

09:02.420 --> 09:11.840
a hen, and in all her behavior proving herself the hen of the woods. The young suddenly disperse

09:11.840 --> 09:19.460
on your approach at a signal from the mother, as if a whirlwind had swept them away, and

09:19.460 --> 09:25.500
they so exactly resemble the dried leaves and twigs that many a traveler has placed

09:25.500 --> 09:31.180
his foot in the midst of a brood, and heard the whirr of the old bird as she flew off,

09:31.440 --> 09:37.500
and her anxious calls and mewing, or seen her trail her wings to attract his attention,

09:38.200 --> 09:44.280
without suspecting their neighborhood. The parent will sometimes roll and spin round

09:44.280 --> 09:50.740
before you in such a dishabil that you cannot for a few moments detect what kind of creature

09:50.740 --> 10:00.760
it is. The young squat still and flat, often running their heads under a leaf, and mind

10:00.760 --> 10:05.400
only their mother's directions given from a distance, nor will your approach make them

10:05.400 --> 10:11.300
run again and betray themselves. You may even tread on them, or have your eyes on them for

10:11.300 --> 10:16.960
a minute without discovering them. I have held them in my open hand at such a time,

10:17.100 --> 10:23.460
and still their only care, obedient to their mother and their instinct, was to squat there

10:23.460 --> 10:32.540
fear or trembling. So perfect is this instinct that once when I had lain them on the leaves

10:32.540 --> 10:38.140
again and one accidentally fell on its side, it was found with the rest in exactly the

10:38.140 --> 10:45.980
same position ten minutes afterward. They are not callow like the young of most birds,

10:45.980 --> 10:54.260
but more perfectly developed and precocious even than chickens. The remarkably adult yet

10:54.260 --> 11:03.060
innocent expression of their open and serene eyes is very memorable. All intelligence seems

11:03.060 --> 11:12.500
reflected in them. They suggest not merely the purity of infancy, but a wisdom clarified

11:12.500 --> 11:22.020
by experience. Such an eye was not born when the bird was, but is co-evil with the sky

11:22.020 --> 11:31.880
it reflects. The woods do not yield another such a gem. The traveller does not often look

11:31.880 --> 11:40.080
into such a limpid well. The ignorant or reckless sportsman often shoots the parent at such

11:40.080 --> 11:51.120
time, and leaves these innocents to fall a prey to some prowling beast or bird, or gradually

11:51.120 --> 11:58.520
mingle with the decaying leaves which they so much resemble. It is said that when hatched

11:58.520 --> 12:05.040
by a hen they will directly disperse on some alarm, and so are lost, for they never hear

12:05.040 --> 12:15.480
the mother's call which gathers them again. These were my hens and chickens. It is remarkable

12:15.480 --> 12:21.580
how many creatures live wild and free, though secret in the woods, and still sustain themselves

12:21.580 --> 12:30.400
in the neighbourhood of towns, suspected by hunters only. How retired the otter manages

12:30.400 --> 12:39.020
to live here. He grows to be four feet long, as big as a small boy, perhaps without any

12:39.020 --> 12:46.860
human being getting a glimpse of him. I formerly saw the raccoon in the woods, behind where

12:46.860 --> 12:53.920
my house is built, and probably still heard their winnowing at night. Commonly I rested

12:53.920 --> 13:00.940
an hour or two in the shade at noon, after planting, and ate my lunch and read a little

13:00.940 --> 13:07.380
by a spring which was the source of a swamp and of a brook, oozing from under Brister's

13:07.380 --> 13:17.460
Hill, half a mile from my field. The approach to this was through a succession of descending

13:18.100 --> 13:27.820
grassy hollows, full of young pitch pines into a larger wood about the swamp. There

13:27.820 --> 13:35.120
in a very secluded and shaded spot, under a spreading white pine, there was yet a clean

13:35.120 --> 13:44.960
firm sward to sit on. I had dug out the spring and made a well of clear grey water, where

13:44.960 --> 13:52.540
I could dip up a pailful without roiling it. And thither I went for this purpose almost

13:52.540 --> 13:59.780
every day in midsummer, when the pond was warmest. Thither, too, the woodcock led her

13:59.780 --> 14:08.520
brood to probe the mud for worms, flying but a foot above them down the bank while they

14:08.520 --> 14:15.700
ran in a troop beneath. But at last spying me, she would leave her young and circle round

14:15.700 --> 14:22.380
and round me, nearer and nearer till within four or five feet, pretending broken wings

14:22.380 --> 14:28.660
and legs to attract my attention, and get off her young, who would already have taken

14:28.660 --> 14:38.280
up their march with faint, wiry peep, single file through the swamp as she directed. Or

14:38.280 --> 14:46.240
I heard the peep of the young when I could not see the parent bird. There, too, the turtle-doves

14:46.240 --> 14:52.380
sat over the spring, or fluttered from bough to bough of the soft white pines over my head,

14:53.120 --> 15:00.440
or the red squirrel, coursing down the nearest bough, was particularly familiar and inquisitive.

15:00.940 --> 15:06.420
You only need sit still long enough in some attractive spot in the woods, that all its

15:06.420 --> 15:09.360
inhabitants may exhibit themselves to you by turns.

15:10.700 --> 15:17.500
I was witness to events of a less peaceful character. One day when I went out to my wood-pile,

15:17.760 --> 15:26.720
or rather my pile of stumps, I observed two large ants, the one red, the other much larger

15:26.720 --> 15:34.580
nearly half an inch long and black, fiercely contending with one another. Having once got

15:34.580 --> 15:41.220
cold, they never let go, but struggled and wrestled and rolled on the chips incessantly.

15:42.660 --> 15:47.420
Looking farther I was surprised to find that the chips were covered with such combatants,

15:48.800 --> 15:58.020
that it was not a doolum, but a bellum, a war between two races of ants, the red always

15:58.020 --> 16:07.320
pitted against the black, and frequently two red ones to one black. The legions of these

16:07.320 --> 16:14.440
Mermidons covered all the hills and vales in my wood-yard, and the ground was already

16:14.440 --> 16:22.400
strewn with the dead and dying, both red and black. It was the only battle which I have

16:22.400 --> 16:31.100
ever witnessed, the only battlefield I ever trod while the battle was raging, internecine

16:31.100 --> 16:43.240
war, the red republicans on the one hand and the black imperialists on the other. On every

16:43.240 --> 16:50.720
side they were engaged in deadly combat, yet without any noise that I could hear, and human

16:50.720 --> 16:58.300
soldiers never fought so resolutely. I watched a couple that were fast locked in each other's

16:58.300 --> 17:05.820
embraces, in a little sunny valley amid the chips, now at noonday prepared to fight till

17:05.820 --> 17:15.240
the sun went down or life went out. The smaller red champion had fastened himself like a vice

17:15.240 --> 17:22.340
to his adversary's front, and through all the tumbling on that field never for an instant

17:22.340 --> 17:28.220
ceased to gnaw at one of his feelers near the root, having already caused the other

17:28.220 --> 17:35.100
to go by the board, while the stronger black one dashed him from side to side, and, as

17:35.100 --> 17:42.580
I saw on looking nearer, had already divested him of several of his members. They fought

17:42.580 --> 17:50.560
with more pertinacity than bulldogs, neither manifested the least disposition to retreat.

17:52.300 --> 18:01.000
It was evident that their battle cry was conquer or die. In the meanwhile there came along

18:01.000 --> 18:07.640
a single red ant on the hillside of this valley, evidently full of excitement, who either had

18:07.640 --> 18:13.440
dispatched his foe or had not yet taken part in the battle, probably the latter, for he

18:13.440 --> 18:20.640
had lost none of his limbs, whose mother had charged him to return with his shield or upon

18:20.640 --> 18:28.780
it. Or, perchance, he was some Achilles, who had nourished his wrath apart, and had now

18:28.780 --> 18:37.620
come to avenge or rescue his Patroclus. He saw this unequal combat from afar, and he

18:37.640 --> 18:42.060
knew that he was not alone, for the blacks were nearly twice the size of the red. He

18:42.060 --> 18:49.960
drew near with rapid pace, till he stood on his guard within half an inch of the combatants.

18:50.900 --> 18:57.180
Then watching his opportunity he sprang upon the black warrior, and commenced his operations

18:57.180 --> 19:05.480
near the root of his right foreleg, leaving the foe to select among his own members. And

19:05.480 --> 19:11.860
so there were three united for life, as if a new kind of attraction had been invented

19:11.860 --> 19:19.760
which put all other locks and cements to shame. I should not have wondered why this time to

19:19.760 --> 19:26.300
find that they had their respective musical bands stationed on some eminent chip, and

19:26.300 --> 19:33.220
playing their national heirs the while, to excite the slow and cheer the dying combatants.

19:33.220 --> 19:42.280
I was myself excited, and somewhat even as if they had been men. The more you think of

19:42.280 --> 19:51.100
it, the less the difference. And certainly there is not the fight recorded in Concord

19:51.100 --> 19:57.540
history, at least, if in the history of America they will bear a moment's comparison with

19:57.540 --> 20:04.420
this, whether for the numbers engaged in it, or for the patriotism and heroism displayed.

20:05.980 --> 20:16.260
For numbers and for carnage it was an Austerlitz, or Dresden, Concord fight. Two killed on the

20:16.260 --> 20:25.840
patriot side, and Luther Blanchard wounded. Why, here every ant was a buttrick. Fire!

20:25.840 --> 20:35.860
For God's sake, fire! And thousands shared the fate of Davis and Hosmer. There was not

20:35.860 --> 20:41.820
one hireling there. I have no doubt that it was a principle they fought for, as much as

20:41.820 --> 20:55.820
our ancestors, and not to avoid a three-penny tax on their tea. And the results of this

20:55.820 --> 20:58.420
battle of Bunker Hill, at least.

20:59.600 --> 21:06.100
I took up the chip, on which the three I have particularly described were struggling, carried

21:06.100 --> 21:10.960
it into my house, and placed it under a tumbler on my windowsill in order to see the issue.

21:12.520 --> 21:18.480
Holding a microscope to the first mentioned red ant, I saw that though he was assiduously

21:18.480 --> 21:24.920
gnawing at the near foreleg of his enemy, having severed his remaining feeler, his own

21:24.920 --> 21:31.060
breast was all torn away, exposing what vitals he had there to the jaws of the black warrior,

21:32.020 --> 21:38.220
whose breastplate was apparently too thick for him to pierce, and the dark carbuncles

21:38.220 --> 21:46.480
of the sufferer's eyes shone with ferocity such as war only could excite. They struggled

21:46.480 --> 21:52.860
half an hour longer under the tumbler, and when I looked again the black soldier had

21:52.860 --> 21:58.520
severed the heads of his foes from their bodies, and the still-living heads were hanging on

21:58.520 --> 22:06.240
either side of him like ghastly trophies at his saddle-bow, still apparently as firmly

22:06.240 --> 22:12.820
fastened as ever, and he was endeavoring with feeble struggles, being without feelers and

22:12.820 --> 22:18.740
with only the remnant of a leg, and I know not how many other wounds, to divest himself

22:18.740 --> 22:24.700
of them, which at length, after half an hour more, he accomplished.

22:26.500 --> 22:33.160
I raised the glass and he went off over the windowsill in that crippled state. Whether

22:33.160 --> 22:39.340
he finally survived that combat and spent the remainder of his days in some Hôtel des

22:39.800 --> 22:47.740
Invalides, I do not know, but I thought that his industry would not be worth much thereafter.

22:48.780 --> 22:56.640
I never learned which party was victorious, nor the cause of the war, but I felt for the

22:56.640 --> 23:03.940
rest of that day as if I had had my feelings excited and harrowed by witnessing the struggle,

23:04.280 --> 23:10.440
the ferocity and carnage of a human battle before my door.

23:12.040 --> 23:18.560
Kirby and Spence tell us that the battles of ants have long been celebrated and the

23:18.560 --> 23:24.640
date of them recorded, though they say that Huber is the only modern author who appears

23:24.640 --> 23:32.140
to have witnessed them. Agnus Silvius, say they, after giving a very circumstantial account

23:32.140 --> 23:37.780
of one contested with great obstinacy by a great and small species on the trunk of a

23:37.780 --> 23:47.640
pear tree, adds that this action was fought in the pontificate of Eugenius IV in the presence

23:47.640 --> 23:54.040
of Nicholas Pistorianus, an eminent lawyer who related the whole history of the battle

23:54.040 --> 24:00.980
with the greatest fidelity. A similar engagement between great and small ants is recorded by

24:00.980 --> 24:07.840
Olaus Magnus, in which the small ones, being victorious, are said to have buried the bodies

24:07.840 --> 24:15.340
of their own soldiers, but left those of their giant enemies a prey to the birds. This event

24:15.340 --> 24:22.580
happened previous to the expulsion of the tyrant Christian II from Sweden. The battle

24:22.580 --> 24:28.740
which I witnessed took place in the presidency of Polk, five years before the passage of

24:28.740 --> 24:30.880
Pistor's fugitive slave Bill.

24:32.500 --> 24:40.540
Many a village boas fit only to course a mud-turtle in a victuling cellar, sported his heavy quarters

24:40.540 --> 24:46.820
in the woods, without the knowledge of his master, and ineffectually smelled at old fox

24:46.820 --> 24:54.400
burrows and wood-chucks' holes, led perchance by some slight kerr which nimbly threaded

24:54.400 --> 25:01.660
the wood, and might still inspire a natural terror in its denizens. Now far behind his

25:01.660 --> 25:07.260
guide, barking like a canine bull towards some small squirrel, which had treated itself

25:07.260 --> 25:13.380
for scrutiny, then cantering off, bending the bushes with his weight, imagining that

25:13.380 --> 25:20.040
he is on the track of some stray member of the Gerbilla family. Once I was surprised

25:20.040 --> 25:26.060
to see a cat walking along the stony shore of the pond, for they rarely wander so far

25:26.060 --> 25:35.140
from the home. The surprise was mutual. Nevertheless, the most domestic cat which is laying on a

25:35.140 --> 25:43.420
rug all her days appears quite at home in the woods, and, by her sly and stealthy behaviour,

25:43.940 --> 25:48.120
proves herself more native there than the regular inhabitants.

25:49.940 --> 25:57.040
Once when burying I met with a cat with young kittens in the woods, quite wild, and they

25:57.040 --> 26:03.860
all, like their mother, had their backs up and were fiercely spitting at me. A few years

26:03.860 --> 26:11.700
before I lived in the woods there was what was called a winged cat, and one of the farmhouses

26:11.700 --> 26:20.100
in Lincoln nearest the pond, Mr. Gillian Bakers. When I called to see her in June, 1842, she

26:20.100 --> 26:26.020
was gone a-hunting in the woods, as was her want. I am not sure whether it was a male

26:26.020 --> 26:32.440
or female, and so use the more common pronoun. But her mistress told me that she came into

26:32.440 --> 26:37.520
the neighborhood a little more than a year before, in April, and was finally taken into

26:37.520 --> 26:45.060
their house, that she was of a dark brownish-grey color, with a white spot on her throat and

26:45.060 --> 26:52.960
white feet, and had a large bushy tail like a fox, that in the winter the fur grew thick

26:52.960 --> 27:00.900
and flatted out along her sides, forming stripes ten or twelve inches long by two and a half

27:00.900 --> 27:09.000
wide, and under her chin like a muff. The upper side, loose, the under matted like felt,

27:09.280 --> 27:16.400
and in the spring these appendages dropped off. They gave me a pair of her wings, which

27:16.400 --> 27:23.880
I keep still. There is no appearance of a membrane about them. Some thought it was part

27:23.880 --> 27:30.020
flying squirrel or some other wild animal, which is not impossible, for according to

27:30.020 --> 27:36.460
naturalists prolific hybrids have been produced by the union of the marten and domestic cat.

27:37.520 --> 27:43.620
This would have been the right kind of cat for me to keep, if I had kept any, for why

27:43.620 --> 27:47.700
should not a poet's cat be winged as well as his horse?

27:48.900 --> 27:57.140
In the fall the loon, Columbus Glacialis, came, as usual, to molt and bathe in the pond,

27:57.600 --> 28:04.800
making the woods ring with his wild laughter before I had risen. At rumor of his arrival

28:04.800 --> 28:11.680
all the mill-dam sportsmen are on the alert, in gigs and on foot, two by two and three

28:11.680 --> 28:18.860
by three, with patent rifles and conical balls and spy-glasses. They come rustling through

28:18.860 --> 28:26.100
the woods like autumn leaves, at least ten men to one loon. Some station themselves on

28:26.100 --> 28:32.540
this side of the pond, some on that, for the poor bird cannot be omnipresent. If he

28:32.540 --> 28:41.660
dive here he must come up there. But now the kind October wind rises, rustling

28:41.660 --> 28:47.600
the leaves and rippling the surface of the water, so that no loon can be heard or seen,

28:48.300 --> 28:55.620
though his foes sweep the pond with spy-glasses and make the woods resound with their discharges.

28:56.760 --> 29:04.180
The waves generously rise and dash angrily, taking sides with all waterfowl, and our sportsmen

29:04.180 --> 29:13.720
must beat a retreat to town and shop and unfinished jobs. But they were too often successful.

29:15.980 --> 29:20.960
When I went to get a pail of water early in the morning I frequently saw this stately

29:20.960 --> 29:29.060
bird sailing out of my cove within a few rods. If I endeavored to overtake him in a boat

29:29.060 --> 29:35.220
in order to see how he would maneuver he would dive and be completely lost, so that I did

29:35.220 --> 29:41.840
not discover him again, sometimes till the latter part of the day. But I was more than

29:41.840 --> 29:49.420
a match for him on the surface. He commonly went off in a rain. As I was paddling along

29:49.420 --> 29:56.900
the north shore one very calm October afternoon, for such days especially they settle on to

29:56.900 --> 30:04.580
the lakes, like the milkweed down, having looked in vain over the pond for a loon, suddenly

30:04.580 --> 30:11.280
one, sailing out from the shore toward the middle a few rods in front of me, set up his

30:11.280 --> 30:18.720
wild laugh and betrayed himself. I pursued with a paddle and he dived, but when he came

30:18.720 --> 30:25.460
up I was nearer than before. He dived again, but I miscalculated the direction he would

30:25.460 --> 30:32.280
take, and we were fifty rods apart when he came to the surface this time, for I had helped

30:32.280 --> 30:40.300
to widen the interval, and again he laughed long and loud, and with more reason than before.

30:41.280 --> 30:48.480
He maneuvered so cunningly that I could not get within half a dozen rods of him. Each

30:48.480 --> 30:54.300
time when he came to the surface, turning his head this way and that, he coolly surveyed

30:54.300 --> 31:00.360
the water and the land, and apparently chose his course so that he might come up where

31:00.360 --> 31:06.780
there was the widest expanse of water and at the greatest distance from the boat. It

31:06.780 --> 31:13.160
was surprising how quickly he made up his mind and put his resolve into execution. He

31:13.160 --> 31:19.600
led me at once to the widest part of the pond and could not be driven from it. While he

31:19.600 --> 31:24.080
was thinking one thing in his brain I was endeavoring to divine his thought in mine.

31:24.720 --> 31:32.080
It was a pretty game, played on the smooth surface of the pond, a man against a loon.

31:33.720 --> 31:39.180
Suddenly, your adversary's checker disappears beneath the board, and the problem is to place

31:39.180 --> 31:45.240
yours nearest to where his will appear again. Sometimes he would come up unexpectedly on

31:45.240 --> 31:51.780
the opposite side of me, having apparently passed directly under the boat. So long-winded

31:51.780 --> 31:57.820
was he, and so unwearable, that when he had swum farthest he would immediately plunge

31:57.820 --> 32:05.400
again, nevertheless, and then no wit could divine where in the deep pond, beneath the

32:05.400 --> 32:12.080
smooth surface, he might be speeding his way like a fish, for he had time and ability to

32:12.080 --> 32:18.440
visit the bottom of the pond in its deepest part. It is said that loons have been caught

32:18.440 --> 32:26.780
in the New York lakes, eighty feet beneath the surface, with hooks set for trout. Though

32:26.780 --> 32:34.320
Walden is deeper than that. How surprised must the fishes be to see this ungainly visitor

32:34.320 --> 32:41.480
from another sphere speeding his way amid their schools! Yet he appeared to know his

32:41.480 --> 32:49.000
course as surely underwater as on the surface, and swam much faster there. Once or twice

32:49.000 --> 32:55.300
I saw a ripple where he approached the surface, just put his head out to reconnoiter, and

32:55.300 --> 33:02.240
instantly dived again. I found that it was as well for me to rest on my oars and wait

33:02.240 --> 33:08.020
his reappearing as to endeavor to calculate where he would rise, for again and again when

33:08.020 --> 33:14.760
I was straining my eyes over the surface one way I would suddenly be startled by his unearthly

33:14.760 --> 33:23.640
laugh behind me. But why, after displaying so much cunning, did he invariably betray himself

33:23.640 --> 33:31.180
the moment he came up by that loud laugh? Did not his white breast enough betray him?

33:31.980 --> 33:39.240
He was indeed a silly loon, I thought. I could commonly hear the splash of the water

33:39.240 --> 33:45.460
when he came up, and so also detected him. But after an hour he seemed as fresh as ever,

33:45.940 --> 33:53.620
dived as willingly, and swam yet farther than at first. It was surprising to see how surreal

33:53.640 --> 34:00.440
he sailed off with unruffled breast when he came to the surface, doing all the work with

34:00.440 --> 34:09.740
his webbed feet beneath. His usual note was this demoniac laughter, yet somewhat like

34:09.740 --> 34:17.240
that of a waterfowl. But occasionally when he had balked me most successfully, and come

34:17.240 --> 34:25.260
up a long way off, he uttered a long-drawn, unearthly howl, probably more like that of

34:25.260 --> 34:31.500
a wolf than any bird, as when a beast puts his muzzle to the ground and deliberately

34:31.500 --> 34:41.420
howls. This was his looning, perhaps the wildest sound that is ever heard here, making the

34:41.420 --> 34:49.800
woods ring far and wide. I concluded that he laughed in derision of my efforts, confident

34:49.800 --> 34:57.180
of his own resources. Though the sky was by this time overcast, the pond was so smooth

34:57.620 --> 35:03.160
that I could see where he broke the surface when I did not hear him. His white breast,

35:03.440 --> 35:09.700
the stillness of the air, and the smoothness of the water were all against him. At length

35:09.700 --> 35:16.320
having come up fifty rods off, he uttered one of those prolonged howls, as if calling

35:16.320 --> 35:24.320
on the god of loons to aid him. And immediately there came a wind from the east, and rippled

35:24.320 --> 35:30.560
the surface, and filled the whole air with misty rain, and I was impressed as if it were

35:30.560 --> 35:39.320
the prayer of the loon answered, and his god was angry with me. And so I left him, disappearing

35:39.320 --> 35:47.420
far away, on the tumultuous surface. For hours in fall days I watched the ducks

35:47.420 --> 35:54.580
cunningly tack and veer and hold the middle of the pond, far from the sportsmen, tricks

35:54.580 --> 36:01.880
which they will have less need to practice in Louisiana bayous. When compelled to rise

36:01.880 --> 36:07.740
they would sometimes circle round and round and over the pond at a considerable height,

36:08.080 --> 36:13.840
from which they could easily see to other ponds in the river, like black motes in the

36:13.840 --> 36:20.440
sky. And when I thought they had gone off thither long since, they would settle down

36:20.440 --> 36:26.600
by a slanting flight of a quarter of a mile on to a distant part which was left free.

36:27.440 --> 36:35.320
But what, beside safety, they got by sailing in the middle of Walden, I do not know, unless

36:35.320 --> 36:39.700
they love its water for the same reason that I do.

